Noun. Alternative form of aa.Adverb. (music) At pleasure; ad libitum. Borrowed from Italian a bene placito ("at pleasure").Noun. Something that is simultaneously a benefit and a burden, or that may seem initially beneficial but also brings unforeseen negative consequences.Noun. (colloquial, UK, Australia, New Zealand) A situation of hedging one's bets, refusing to commit to either side of a question.Adjective. (US, idiomatic) Too late and too feeble to achieve the desired effect.Noun. (Australia, slang) Alternative form of a kangaroo loose in the top paddock.Adjective. Drunk. See three sheets to the wind.Verb. Alternative form of call a spade a spade.Verb. Synonym of close the stable door after the horse has bolted.Verb. (slang, derogatory, idiomatic) Of a person: to become extremely unattractive.Preposition. Used as an intensifier to emphasize typicality of behavior.Noun. A paradox of deontic logic, whereby the plausible statements (i) if you murder, you ought to murder gently, (ii) you do commit murder, and (iii) to murder gently you must murder, imply the less plausible statement (iv) you ought to murder.Verb. (Australia, colloquial, vulgar) To annoy or frustrate someone to a great degree.Verb. Alternative form of go around the houses.Verb. Alternative form of go over like a lead balloon.Verb. (idiomatic) To enjoy oneself greatly; to have a very good time.Verb. (idiomatic) To face a large task or project.Verb. Alternative form of have the world by the tail.Noun. Alternative form of if it looks like a duck, swims like a duck, and quacks like a duck, then it probably is a duck.Verb. Alternative form of know one's ass from a hole in the ground.Verb. (idiomatic) To insist on the total realization of a goal and reject any compromise, thereby decreasing the chance of achieving even a part of that goal.Verb. (idiomatic, UK) To look very disappointed. In pre-decimal British money, a sixpence was worth half a shilling.Verb. (intransitive, British, informal, humorous) To look extremely dishevelled.Verb. (idiomatic, dated) To look annoyed or displeased. A shilling was worth 12 pence, so this would represent a loss of money.Verb. (idiomatic) To do things in one's own way regardless of societal norms and conventional expectations.Adjective. (simile) Extremely nervous. A more elaborate form of nervous as a cat; the implication is that the cat is afraid of its long tail being caught underneath a rocker.Noun. (UK, law) A hypothetical person having the normal skills and knowledge in a particular technical field, without being a genius; used in a legal test related to patents.Noun. Synonym of pilot monitoring.Verb. (slang, vulgar) To waste or squander (money, talent, opportunity, etc.).Verb. (transitive, idiomatic) To accuse or blame (someone).Noun. (British) A snack food, normally available in pubs, made from cured pork skin that has been salted and deep-fried.Verb. (idiomatic) To prevent others from attaining or benefiting from the same advantages, opportunities, or rights as oneself.Verb. Synonym of close the stable door after the horse has bolted.Verb. Synonym of trust someone as far as one could throw them.